T1  - Access to Capital, Capital Structure, and the Funding of the Firm
AU  - BRAV, OMER
Y1  - 2009/02/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01434.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 263
EP  - 308
VL  - 64
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01434.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Based upon a large data set of public and private firms in the United Kingdom, I find that compared to their public counterparts, private firms rely almost exclusively on debt financing, have higher leverage ratios, and tend to avoid external capital markets, leading to a greater sensitivity of their capital structures to fluctuations in performance. I argue that these differences are due to private equity being more costly than public equity. I further examine the private firms subsample to show that private equity is more costly than its public counterpart due to information asymmetry and the desire to maintain control.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Do Entrenched Managers Pay Their Workers More?
AU  - CRONQVIST, HENRIK
AU  - HEYMAN, FREDRIK
AU  - NILSSON, MATTIAS
AU  - SVALERYD, HELENA
AU  - VLACHOS, JONAS
Y1  - 2009/02/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01435.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 309
EP  - 339
VL  - 64
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01435.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Analyzing a panel that matches public firms with worker-level data, we find that managerial entrenchment affects workers' pay. CEOs with more control pay their workers more, but financial incentives through cash flow rights ownership mitigate such behavior. Entrenched CEOs pay more to employees closer to them in the corporate hierarchy, geographically closer to the headquarters, and associated with conflict-inclined unions. The evidence is consistent with entrenched CEOs paying more to enjoy private benefits such as lower effort wage bargaining and improved social relations with employees. Our results show that managerial ownership and corporate governance can play an important role for employee compensation.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Labor and Corporate Governance: International Evidence from Restructuring Decisions
AU  - ATANASSOV, JULIAN
AU  - KIM, E. HAN
Y1  - 2009/02/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01436.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 341
EP  - 374
VL  - 64
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01436.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Our results highlight the importance of interaction among management, labor, and investors in shaping corporate governance. We find that strong union laws protect not only workers but also underperforming managers. Weak investor protection combined with strong union laws are conducive to worker?management alliances, wherein poorly performing firms sell assets to prevent large-scale layoffs, garnering worker support to retain management. Asset sales in weak investor protection countries lead to further deteriorating performance, whereas in strong investor protection countries they improve performance and lead to more layoffs. Strong union laws are less effective in preventing layoffs when financial leverage is high.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Market Sidedness: Insights into Motives for Trade Initiation
AU  - SARKAR, ASANI
AU  - SCHWARTZ, ROBERT A.
Y1  - 2009/02/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01437.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 375
EP  - 423
VL  - 64
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2008.01437.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We infer motives for trade initiation from market sidedness. We define trading as more two-sided (one-sided) if the correlation between the number of buyer- and seller-initiated trades increases (decreases), and assess changes in sidedness (relative to a control sample) around events that identify trade initiators. Consistent with asymmetric information, trading is more one-sided before merger news. Consistent with belief heterogeneity, trading is more two-sided before earnings and macro announcements with greater dispersion in analyst forecasts, and after news with larger announcement surprises. We examine the codeterminacy of sidedness, bid-ask spread, volatility, number of trades, and order imbalance.
ER  - 

